	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>Alright, Sinari got it, but it seems most of the rest of you missed the point of the post.<br />
<br />
<b>This is not an exercise in listing to me what you think a wizard isn't good at.</b><br />
<br />
I knew as soon as the thought for this post entered my head that if I wasn't very clear up front with what I wanted to discuss, people would turn this into a gripe session, as almost every other thread on these boards.  I'm not interested one bit in hearing- in this thread at least- a blanket list of the things you think you aren't good at.  I'm also not interested in hearing the various comments from people trying to cram me into an &quot;opposition&quot; camp- /wave Mookus.  (For what it's worth, I don't think any class should be able to solo as effectively as they group, but that's neither here nor there.)<br />
<br />
What I'm trying to steer this towards is a discussion about what traits a wizards should lack; or what traits a wizard can improve upon- that encourage him to seek out a group.  I'm well aware that wizards have low hp, but that's not exactly a factor that either gives them difficulty outside of groups (much difficulty) or gets improved upon making the wizard a more powerful player while grouping.  I'm well aware that wizards can't heal, but that's not an issue of a weakness more than it is one of definition.  Fish were not meant to climb trees, but they still have a defined role in the ecosystem.<br />
<br />
As well this is <b>not</b> a discussion about what weaknesses to add to the wizard class.  Some of you people are so desperate to start an argument with me that you saw the title of the post and started your argument (/wave Natan- awfully interested in talking now, hrm? <img src="images/smilies/rolleyes.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Roll Eyes (Sarcastic)" class="inlineimg" /> )<br />
<br />
If you are uncomfortable with discussing how wizards get improved upon by other players, please do not deign to discuss class balance.  Interreliance is a fundamental building block of MMORPG's, and you can't get a good grasp on one side of the coin without understanding the other.<br />
<br />
(On a note about soloing- in a perfect world, all classes would be able to solo, and they'd all get exp from it that was ok, but nothing like grouping.  Unfortunately, it is not a perfect world, and some classes are left overpowered solo while others are left w/o an ability to solo.  Controlled soloing is good for the game, but it's always a good idea to make grouping be more effective.)</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
