		<!-- message -->
		<div><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Rann</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">I really like this response in it's entirety. I think claud may be referring to measures to ensure the wizard can't solo..(or that it's less attractive than grouping) I think it's a non issue, I think those measures are in place.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				I'm curious as to what your opinions are on what checks the game should have to encourage wizards to group, beyond gamewide ones such as the grouping xp modifier and social reasons.
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
<br />
Earning experience is only one aspect of character progression, and character progression is only one aspect of what makes gameplay &quot;rewarding&quot;.<br />
<br />
Other than <i>vendor garbage</i> or &quot;pp&quot;, there is very little by way of loot, gear upgrades or augments, or spells that can be obtained by soloing which is level appropriate.  Few worthy quests can be completed solo that are as rewarding as those quests that require a group, or raid.<br />
<br />
Soloing is no longer the most effective means to earn experience, either.  Balanced groups can maintain a higher amount of kills of more experience rewarding mobs than a solo player can with less risk involved and less downtime all around.<br />
<br />
While the social aspect of grouping as opposed to soloing<i>is</i> a given, I think it does deserve consideration as a strong factor because this is the very reason we are playing EverQuest as opposed to a single player game on a console device.  I don't know any player that would rather solo than participate in a group with friends.<br />
<br />
While the ability to solo is convenient, the rewards from grouping are so much greater than those from soloing as to warrant the &quot;extra effort&quot; and/or necessary intrapersonal management.<br />
<br />
In the case of Wizards, the simple fact is one that spends all their time soloing is going to be at a severe disadvantage to one fortunate enough to constantly fill a position in a group with friends.  The one involved in groups will more likely have their latest spells, and will be able to obtain upgrades in a nonraid environment, will be able to engage more content, and will earn more experience and develop a greater knowledge of the game in general.<br />
<br />
I don't think there is a need for a particular class <i>weakness</i> to necessitate grouping.  Grouping has plenty of incentives by it's own right.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
